# reboot_plan.conf — ORCHESTRATOR-SIDE rolling reboot plan
#
# Lives on the orchestrator VM (the one that runs bin/rolling_reboot_next.sh
# from cron). Copy to reboot_plan.conf and edit. reboot_plan.conf is
# git-ignored.
#
# Format — one entry per line:
#     <DC-LABEL>  <manager-ip>
#
# Rules:
#   - <DC-LABEL> MUST match a [section] in datacenters.conf
#   - <manager-ip> MUST exist in that DC jump's managers.conf
#   - Order = reboot order. Group by cluster to spread risk: never reboot
#     two managers of the same cluster back-to-back (since the cron runs
#     daily, the natural 24h gap already covers KB 396719 reconciliation,
#     but operators usually still interleave clusters as defense-in-depth).
#   - One entry is rebooted per cron firing (see bin/install_orchestrator_cron.sh).
#   - Comments start with '#'. Blank lines ignored.
#
# Example for 2 DCs, 3 clusters of 3 managers each = 18 entries / 18 days:
#
# # --- DC-A ---
# DC-A 192.168.20.10        # GER1 master
# DC-B 192.168.30.10        # interleave: GER1 of DC-B
# DC-A 192.168.20.11        # GER1 second of DC-A
# DC-B 192.168.30.11
# DC-A 192.168.20.12
# DC-B 192.168.30.12
# # --- next cluster ---
# DC-A 192.168.21.10        # GER2 master
# DC-B 192.168.31.10
# ...
#
# After the plan completes the cron stops doing anything until you run:
#   ./bin/rolling_reboot_next.sh --reset --yes
# (typically you would also edit this file first, e.g. to update IPs after
#  a cluster rebuild.)
